{% extends 'base.html.twig' %}
{% set nav = 'transparency' %}

{% block title %}The treaty-wide ask · A joint letter to the Fund · Robinson Huron Treaty{% endblock %}
{% block description %}One joint, respectful request from beneficiaries across the treaty to the Robinson Huron Treaty Litigation Fund: the disbursement agreement, the trustees and how they are chosen, the amendment rules, and what reporting beneficiaries receive.{% endblock %}

{% block hero %}
<section class="hero">
  <div class="wrap wrap--wide">
    <p class="eyebrow">Treaty-wide</p>
    <h1>A joint letter to the Fund.</h1>
    <p class="lead">Members from across the treaty asking the Robinson Huron Treaty Litigation Fund, together and with respect, to show how our shared settlement is governed. One voice, so no community asks alone.</p>
  </div>
</section>
{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
  <p>In 2023 the Robinson Huron Treaty First Nations reached a ten billion dollar settlement for unpaid annuities, the largest sum our communities have ever held, shared across all 21 signatory nations. The Litigation Fund is the body that pursued and now helps administer that settlement at the treaty-wide level.</p>
  <p>We are grateful for the work that brought the settlement about, and we want to see it governed openly, for us and for the generations coming. This page is the joint letter the Circle puts to the Fund. It is a request to understand, not a challenge.</p>

  <div class="card">
    <h3>What we ask the Fund to share</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>The compensation and disbursement agreement that controls how the settlement is shared among the First Nations, in full.</li>
      <li>The current list of trustees of the Fund, how each trustee is chosen, and the length of their terms.</li>
      <li>The process for amending the disbursement agreement, including the threshold of trustees required, and a record of any amendments made to date.</li>
      <li>A description of the financial reporting beneficiaries receive about the Fund, and how often it is provided.</li>
      <li>How decisions are made about what is distributed collectively versus paid to individual members, and how members can have input into those decisions.</li>
      <li>The contact and the process by which a member may ask questions of the Fund or raise a concern.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>

  <h2>How we ask</h2>
  <p>We ask that this information be made available to beneficiaries in plain form. A clear, written response would let members across the treaty see that our settlement is held and governed transparently, which serves everyone, the Fund included. These are questions, not accusations. Asking to see how our settlement is governed is our right as beneficiaries.</p>

  <div class="card card--coral">
    <h3>Status</h3>
    <p>The joint letter is in draft and circulating among members for sign-on. Community contacts are added as signatories before it is sent. If you would like your community represented on it, please <a href="/get-involved">get involved</a>.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>Background</h2>
  <p>For members who want the fuller picture behind the ask:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><a href="/treaty">The Robinson Huron Treaty, in plain language</a>: what the treaty is, what is settled, what is still being decided, and what each piece means.</li>
    <li><a href="/treaty/distribution-models">Distribution models</a>: the per-capita, collective, and hybrid approaches side by side, and the questions each one has to answer to be fair to the whole membership.</li>
  </ul>

